We'd like to clarify something that has come up recently, and we already discussed weeks ago, but I'll do it again. We have a **small internal team of developers** working on a web agent because one of the subnet goals is to have **the best web agent ever**. This helps us explore new ideas such as **RL-based agents** with **vision capabilities**, and push innovation forward.

**IM is and will remain completely fair**, everything is **public, transparent**, and open for **anyone** to review.

This agent **was deregistered for several months**,because competition is tough. This is great because it forces us to keep improving the agent and understand the new approaches, started performing better. 

We completely understand that some community members may have had doubts, and we take responsibility for **not communicating this more clearly earlier on**. We've already spoken with several miners about this, explaining that our focus has been on strengthening **Dynamic**, **Open Source transparency**, and the **Leaderboard**, to make the competition **tougher, fairer, and more meaningful for everyone**.

We've always done our best to **support every miner** through each update. The recent **documentation and onboarding improvements** make it much easier for new miners to join, learn, and start testing locally, even without a testnet.

Miners should start **pivoting toward more generalized and adaptive agent solutions**, and even explore **Reinforcement Learning environments**, to be prepared for the **upcoming new IM and IWA tasks**. This is fully aligned with the **new model** we've been gradually pivoting to.

Our goal remains the same: to keep everything **open, fair, and transparent**, while working together to build the **best and most advanced web agent ecosystem possible**.

For anyone who wants to continue discussing this topic, please feel free to reach out to us privately and we'll be happy to talk about it.
Now, back to what really matters, the work being done and the progress achieved over the last week. 🚀

**PROGRESS UPDATE**:

* 🌐 **New Web Version**, uploaded after fixing a small issue in one of the use cases that caused a short delay. Everything is now stable and running smoothly.

* 🤖 **Chutes Integration**, now live! Alongside OpenAI, miners and validators can use **Chutes** as their LLM provider for benchmark task generation.

* 📚 **Documentation & Onboarding**, completely reworked to make it easier for new miners to start and test locally, without needing a testnet. Check out the updated miner documentation here: https://github.com/autoppia/autoppia_web_agents_subnet/blob/main/docs/miner.md

* 🧪 **Benchmark Framework**, simplified and improved so everyone can develop and test their web agents quickly and safely before deploying as miners.
https://github.com/autoppia/autoppia_web_agents_subnet/blob/main/docs/benchmark-README.md

* 🔄 **Dynamic & WTA**, Dynamic is complete ✅ and WTA is currently under testing. Once Web13 is finalized, we'll move fully into the dynamic phase.

* 🏆 **Leaderboard Update**, We know this is something **everyone has been waiting for**, and we don't want to disappoint. We're putting a lot of effort into this, maybe even more than what's needed for a first version, but we want to make sure it meets expectations from day one. 💪 

The idea is to make it **super easy for new miners to enter the competition**. You'll be able to **test your agent directly from the web**, even **without needing Bittensor**, we'll be able to **run benchmarks just from the web** by providing host and port!

We're also sharing some 📸 **dashboard screenshots and previews** so you can see all the ongoing work behind the scenes, a lot of effort that's not always visible, but it's moving in the right direction.

Everything we're building aims to make participation **easier**, competition **fairer**, and the ecosystem **stronger** for everyone. 💪🌍

We tried also to explained that we *do* have an internal team of 2 devs allocated to develop a Web Agent. And yes,  their Web Agent recently reached top positions in the subnet. Respectfully, I believe you are wrong. Winner takes it all or TopK winner takes it all will reduce UID pressure because rewards will not be linked to how many UIDs a miner team has. TopK vs Top1 was disccussed here "https://x.com/_olaige/status/1971817725614862803?t=MdhK1mYoEQoYp2fL8UoqJA&s=19" and we are implementing exactly that. A way to differentiate miner outputs so we ensure TopK does not belong to same team / is the same solution.
